  "prompt": "What is a masala bond?",
  "response": "A masala bond is a type of debt instrument issued outside of India by Indian entities, but it is denominated in Indian rupees rather than the local currency. The bonds are typically issued to raise capital in overseas markets, and they enable Indian companies to access foreign investors while avoiding the risk of exchange rate fluctuations since the repayment is in rupees.\n\nMasala bonds are aimed at the international market, and they help in broadening the pool of potential investors. By issuing bonds in their own currency, Indian entities can potentially attract those investors who are optimistic about the Indian economy and expect the rupee to either appreciate or remain stable over time.\n\nThe concept of masala bonds was introduced by the International Finance Corporation (IFC), a member of the World Bank Group, in November 2014. They contribute to the deepening of the Indian bond market by providing an alternative route for financing in local currency.\n\nThe term \"masala\" refers to the variety of spices used in Indian cuisine, symbolizing the diverse nature of the Indian culture, and in this context, it signifies the flavor of India that these bonds bring to global investors.",
